===Season 2 (2010)===
{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race (season 2)}}
[[File:Tyra Sánchez (fan art).jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Tyra Sanchez]]]]

For season two, the number of contestants was increased from nine to twelve, and the prizes were slightly modified: a lifetime supply of Nyx Cosmetics and be the face of nyxcosmetics.com, an exclusive one year public relations contract with [[LGBT]] firm Project Publicity, be featured an LA Eyeworks campaign, join the [[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]] Drag Race tour, and a cash prize of $25,000. A new tradition of writing a farewell message in lipstick on the workstation mirror was started by the first eliminated queen of the season, [[Shangela Laquifa Wadley]]. The theme song playing during the runway and the end credits every episode is "[[Jealous of My Boogie]]" from RuPaul's album ''[[Champion (RuPaul album)|Champion]]''. Each week's episode is followed by a behind-the-scenes show, ''RuPaul's Drag Race Untucked''. The winner of the second season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' was [[Tyra Sanchez]], with [[Pandora Boxx]] winning Miss Congeniality.

On December 6, 2011, [[Amazon.com]] released this season on DVD via their CreateSpace program.<ref name=Amazon.com>{{cite web|last=Kline|first=Dill|title=Rupauls' Drag Race Season 2 Pre-Orders|url=https://www.amazon.com/RuPauls-Drag-Race-Season-2/dp/B005UQQR06/ref=sr_1_6?ie=UTF8&qid=1319228919&sr=8-6|accessdate=August 17, 2015}}</ref>
<!-- To edit the episodes in this section, you need to edit the article listed above. -->

===Season 3 (2011)===
{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race (season 3)}}
[[File:Raja Gemini.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Sutan Amrull|Raja]]]]

This season had [[Michelle Visage]] replacing Merle Ginsberg at the judge's table and Billy Brasfield<ref>{{cite web|last=Brasfield|first=Billy|url=http://www.billybbeauty.com/site/bio_all.html|title=Billy Brasfield Official Biography}}</ref> (better known as Billy B), [[Mike Ruiz]], and Jeffrey Moran (courtesy of [[Absolut Vodka]]) filling in for [[Santino Rice|Santino Rice's]] absence during several episodes. Billy B, celebrity makeup artist and star of the [[HGTV]] mini-series ''Hometown Renovation'', appeared as a judge in five episodes. Whereas Mike Ruiz only judged for two episodes, and Jeffrey Moran for one, Moran only appearing for promotional reasons. Due to Billy B's continued appearances, he and Rice are now considered to have been alternate judges for the same seat at the judges table.<ref name="billyb">{{cite web|url=http://www.logotv.com/video/episode-16-season-3-reunited/1662947/playlist.jhtml#vid=647523|title=Ep. 16, Episode 16, Season 3: Reunited!|publisher=[[Logo TV]]|accessdate=August 17, 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107020503/http://www.logotv.com/video/episode-16-season-3-reunited/1662947/playlist.jhtml#vid=647523|archivedate=November 7, 2014|df=}}</ref> Other changes made included the introduction of a wildcard contestant from the past season, Shangela; an episode with no elimination; and a contestant, [[Carmen Carrera]], being brought back into the competition after having been eliminated a few episodes prior. A new pit crew was also introduced consisting of Jason Carter and Shawn Morales. The theme song playing during the runway every episode was changed to "Champion" while the song playing during the credits is "Main Event", both from RuPaul's album ''[[Champion (RuPaul album)|Champion]]''. As with [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 2)|the previous season]], each week's episode was followed by a behind-the-scenes show, ''[[#Under the Hood and Untucked|RuPaul's Drag Race: Untucked]]''. The winner of the third season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' was [[Raja Gemini|Raja]], with [[Yara Sofia]] winning Miss Congeniality.

On December 6, 2011 Amazon.com released this season on DVD via their CreateSpace program.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kline|first=Dill|url=https://www.amazon.com/RuPauls-Drag-Race-Season-3/dp/B005UQQRBA/ref=sr_1_6?s=movies-tv&ie=UTF8&qid=1319310966&sr=1-6|title=RuPauls Drag Race Season 3|accessdate=August 17, 2015}}</ref>
<!-- To edit the episodes in this section, you need to edit the article listed above. -->

===Season 4 (2012)===
{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race (season 4)}}
[[File:Rupaul Dragcon 2018-281 (41377497904).jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Sharon Needles]]]]

The fourth season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' began airing on January 30, 2012,<ref name="announce">{{cite web |url=http://www.newnownext.com/rupauls-drag-race-season-4-judges-glee-modern-family-amber-riley-jesse-tyler-ferguson/10/2011/ | title = RuPaul's Drag Race Season 4 Judges: Think Glee, Modern Family! | accessdate = October 12, 2011 | last = Polly | first = John | date = October 10, 2011 | work = NewNowNext | publisher = [[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]]}}</ref> with cast members announced November 13, 2011.<ref name="cast">{{cite web |url=http://www.logotv.com/shows/rupauls_drag_race/season_4/series.jhtml | title = Rupaul's Drag Race Season 4 | accessdate = November 15, 2011 | publisher = [[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]]}}</ref> The winner of season four will headline [[Logo (TV channel)|Logo's]] Drag Race Tour featuring [[Absolut Vodka]], wins a one-of-a-kind trip, a lifetime supply of NYX Cosmetics, a cash prize of [[United States dollar|$]]100,000, and the title of "America's Next Drag Superstar."<ref name="press1">{{cite web |url=http://www.logopressroom.com/press-release/halleloo-%E2%80%9Crupaul%E2%80%99s-drag-race%E2%80%9D-returns-to-logo-for-a-new-season-of-outrageous-reality-competition-in-january-2012/|title=HALLELOO! "RUPAUL’S DRAG RACE" RETURNS TO LOGO FOR A NEW SEASON OF OUTRAGEOUS REALITY COMPETITION IN JANUARY 2012|accessdate=August 17, 2015|last=Shumaker|first=Jason|author2=Jake Slane |date=November 14, 2011|work=Logo Press Room|publisher=[[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]]}}</ref> Like the last season, Santino Rice & Billy B (Billy Brasfield), celebrity makeup artist and star of the [[HGTV]] mini-series ''Hometown Renovation'', shared the same seat at the judges table alternatively, Brasfield filling in for Rice when needed.<ref name="billyb"/> Both judges appeared side-by-side in the audience during the "Reunited" episode. The winner of the fourth season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' was [[Sharon Needles]], with [[Latrice Royale]] winning Miss Congeniality.

The theme song playing during the runway every episode was "Glamazon" and the song played during the credits was "The Beginning", both from RuPaul's album ''[[Glamazon (album)|Glamazon]]''.
<!-- To edit the episodes in this section, you need to edit the article listed above. -->

===Season 5 (2013)===
{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race (season 5)}}
[[File:Jinkx Monsoon 08.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Jinkx Monsoon]]]]

The fifth season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' began airing on January 28, 2013, with a 90-minute premiere episode. It had the most contestants since the creation of the show with fourteen.

Season five's winner walked away with the title of "America's Next Drag Superstar" along with a lifetime supply of Colorevolution Cosmetics, a one-of-a-kind trip courtesy of AlandChuck.travel, a headlining spot on [[Logo (TV channel)|Logo's]] Drag Race Tour featuring [[Absolut Vodka]] and a cash prize of $100,000. Santino Rice and Michelle Visage were back as judges at the panel.<ref name='Press1'>{{cite web|url=http://www.logopressroom.com/press-release/rpdr5premiere/|title ="THE QUEENS OF "RUPAUL’S DRAG RACE" SEASON FIVE BEGIN THEIR BATTLE FOR THE CROWN ON MONDAY, JANUARY 28 ON LOGO|accessdate=August 17, 2015|last=Shumaker|first=Jason|author2=Jake Slane|date= December 10, 2012|work=Logo Press Room|publisher=[[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]]}}</ref> The theme song playing during the runway every episode is "I Bring the Beat", while the song playing during the credits is "The Beginning", both songs are from RuPaul's album ''[[Glamazon (album)|Glamazon]]''. The winner of the fifth season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' was [[Jinkx Monsoon]], with [[Ivy Winters]] winning Miss Congeniality.
<!-- To edit the episodes in this section, you need to edit the article listed above. -->

===Season 6 (2014)===
{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race (season 6)}}
[[File:Bianca Del Rio, Rolodex of Hate Tour, Theater Amsterdam 2015.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Bianca Del Rio]]]]

The sixth season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' began airing February 24, 2014. Like [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 5)|the fifth season]], the season featured 14 contestants competing for the title of "America's Next Drag Superstar". For the first time in the show's history, the season premiere was split into two episodes; the fourteen queens are split into two groups and the seven queens into each group compete against each other before being united as one group for the third episode.

Santino Rice and Michelle Visage are back as judges at the panel. Two new pit crew members, Miles Moody and Simon Sherry-Wood, joined Jason Carter and Shawn Morales.<ref>{{cite web | url =
http://www.out.com/entertainment/popnography/2014/02/19/meet-rupauls-drag-races-new-bulgier-pit-crew| title = Meet RuPaul's Drag Race's New, Bulgier Pit Crew | accessdate = February 22, 2014 | last = Lambe | first = Stacy | date = February 19, 2014 | work = out.com, Popnography}}</ref> The winner of this season won a prize package that included a supply from Colorevolution Cosmetics and a cash prize of $100,000.<ref name='Press2'>{{cite web | url =
http://www.logopressroom.com/uncategorized/let-the-transformations-beginrupauls-drag-race-returns-to-logo-tv-for-a-sixth-season-on-monday-february-24th-at-9-pm-etpt/| title = "LET THE TRANSFORMATIONS BEGIN!..."RUPAULS DRAG RACE" RETURNS TO LOGO TV FOR A SIXTH SEASON ON MONDAY, FEBRUARY 24TH AT 9 PM ET/PT | accessdate = January 13, 2014 | last = Shumaker | first = Jason |author2=Jake Slane  | date = January 13, 2014 | work = Logo Press Room | publisher = [[Logo (TV channel)|Logo]]}}</ref> This was also the first season where [[Absolut Vodka]] and Interior Illusions, Inc. were not sponsors for the show, more specifically for the [[RuPaul's Drag Race#Under the Hood and Untucked|Untucked]] episodes. The Interior Illusions Lounge is now simply known as the Silver Lounge or FormDecor Lounge. The theme song played during the runway segment every episode was "Sissy That Walk" while the song playing during the credits is "Dance With U", both from the album ''[[Born Naked]]''. The winner of the sixth season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' was [[Bianca Del Rio]], with [[BenDeLaCreme]] winning Miss Congeniality.
<!-- To edit the episodes in this section, you need to edit the article listed above. -->

===Season 7 (2015)===
{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race (season 7)}}
[[File:Violet Chachki at DragCon, April 2017.png|thumb|right|upright|[[Violet Chachki]]]]

The seventh season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' began airing on March 2, 2015.

Returning judges included [[RuPaul]] and [[Michelle Visage]], while the space previously occupied by [[Santino Rice]] was filled by new additions [[Ross Mathews]] and [[Carson Kressley]].<ref name=HuffPost>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/01/28/drag-race-season-seven-premiere_n_6555636.html|title='RuPaul's Drag Race' Adds New Judges, Will Premiere March 2|accessdate=August 17, 2015|date=January 28, 2015|publisher=Huffington Post}}</ref> Mathews and Kressley were both present for the season premiere and then took turns sharing judging responsibilities. Shawn Morales, a member of the Pit Crew since [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 3)|the third season]] and Simon Sherry-Wood, a member in [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 6)|the sixth season]], did not appear this season and were replaced by Bryce Eilenberg.

Like the previous two seasons of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'', the season featured 14 contestants competing for the title of "America's Next Drag Superstar", a one-year supply of Anastasia Beverly Hills cosmetics and a cash prize of $100,000. The season premiere debuted with a live and same-day viewership of 348,000, a 20% increase from the previous season. On March 20, 2015, it was announced that LogoTV had given the series an early renewal for an eighth season.<ref name="s7">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/rupauls-drag-race-season-8-renewal-1201456543/ |title=‘RuPaul's Drag Race’ Renewed for Season 8 at Logo |accessdate=August 17, 2015 |publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]}}</ref> The winner of the seventh season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' was [[Violet Chachki]], with [[Katya Zamolodchikova|Katya]] winning Miss Congeniality.
<!-- To edit the episodes in this section, you need to edit the article listed above. -->

===Season 8 (2016)===
{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race (season 8)}}
[[File:Bob The Drag Queen at Rupaul's Dragcon 2017 by dvsross.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Bob the Drag Queen]]]]

On January 14, 2016, it was announced that the cast for the eighth season will be revealed during the 2016 [[NewNowNext Awards|New Now Next Honors]] on February 1, 2016, followed by the season premiere on March 7, 2016. The first episode celebrated the 100th taping of the show, and the 100th drag queen to enter the work room. Michelle Visage returned as a main judge, while Carson Kressley and Ross Mathews returned as rotating main judges.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Avery|first1=Dan|title=The Cast Of ''RuPaul{{’}}s Drag Race'' Season 8 Will Be Announced At New Now Next Honors|url=http://www.newnownext.com/the-cast-of-rupauls-drag-race-season-8-will-be-announced-at-new-now-next-honors/01/2016/|website=New Now Next|publisher=[[Viacom International Inc.]]|accessdate=January 14, 2016|location=United States|date=January 14, 2016}}</ref> Similar to the [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 2)|second season]] of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'', the season featured 12 contestants competing for the title of "America's Next Drag Superstar", a one-year supply of Anastasia Beverly Hills cosmetics and a cash prize of $100,000. The winner of the eighth season of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' was [[Bob the Drag Queen]], with [[Cynthia Lee Fontaine]] winning Miss Congeniality.
<!-- To edit the episodes in this section, you need to edit the article listed above. -->

===Season 9 (2017)===
{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race (season 9)}}
[[File:Rupaul Dragcon 2018-164 (41356430574).jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Sasha Velour]]]]

On February 2, 2017, the cast for the ninth season was announced. On March 1, 2017, it was announced that the ninth season would premiere on March 24, the ninth season features 14 contestants competing for the title of "America's Next Drag Superstar", a one-year supply of Anastasia Beverly Hills cosmetics and a cash prize of $100,000. The ninth season aired on VH1, with encore presentations continuing to air on Logo.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|title=''RuPaul’s Drag Race'' Moves From Logo To VH1, More Viacom Show Shifts To Come?|url=http://deadline.com/2017/03/rupauls-drag-race-moves-logo-vh1-viacom-series-shift-1202032976/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|accessdate=March 1, 2017|location=United States|date=March 1, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Gennis|first1=Sadie|title=''RuPaul's Drag Race'' Gets Season 9 Premiere Date — and a New Network!|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/rupauls-drag-race-gets-season-9-premiere-vh1/|website=[[TVGuide]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=March 1, 2017|location=United States|language=en|date=March 1, 2017}}</ref> This season featured the return of [[Cynthia Lee Fontaine]], who previously participated in the series' eighth season. The ninth season featured a top four in the finale episode, as opposed to the top three, which was previously established in the fourth season. The winner of the ninth season of RuPaul's Drag Race was [[Sasha Velour]]. Valentina won Miss Congeniality.

===Season 10 (2018) ===
{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race (season 10)}}
[[File:Aquaria, drag queen, 2018.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Aquaria (drag queen)|Aquaria]]]]

On April 13, 2017, VH1 renewed the series for a tenth season. The season began airing on March 22, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Andreeva|first1=Nellie|title=VH1 Renews ''RuPaul’s Drag Race'', Picks Up Ricky Martin Reality Series – Upfront|url=http://deadline.com/2017/04/vh1-renews-rupauls-drag-race-daytime-divas-premiere-date-ricky-martin-lance-bass-1202068470/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|accessdate=April 13, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170414014619/http://deadline.com/2017/04/vh1-renews-rupauls-drag-race-daytime-divas-premiere-date-ricky-martin-lance-bass-1202068470/|archivedate=April 14, 2017|location=United States|date=April 13, 2017}}</ref> [[Eureka O'Hara]], who was removed from the ninth season due to injury, returned to the show after she accepted an open invitation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2017/04/21/rupauls-drag-race-eureka-returning-season-10-exit-interview/|title=Drag Race's Surprise Eliminee: 'I'm Definitely Going Back' for Season 10|last=Swift|first=Andy|last2=Swift|first2=Andy|date=2017-04-22|website=TVLine|access-date=2017-05-11}}</ref> The tenth season of ''Drag Race'' premiered; alongside the televised return of ''Untucked''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nolfi|first=Joey|title=RuPaul's Drag Race&nbsp;season 10 and&nbsp;Untucked&nbsp;will sashay to VH1 in March|url=http://ew.com/tv/2018/02/16/rupauls-drag-race-season-10-premiere-date/|publisher=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=February 16, 2018}}</ref> On this  season, 14 contestants are again competing for the title of "America's Next Drag Superstar", a one-year supply of Anastasia Beverly Hills cosmetics and a cash prize of $100,000. The winner of the tenth season of RuPaul's Drag Race was [[Aquaria (drag queen)|Aquaria]]. [[Monét X Change]] won Miss Congeniality.

===Season 11 ===
On June 13, 2018, VH1 renewed the series, alongside ''Untucked'', for an eleventh season.<ref>{{cite web |last=Swift |first=Andy |title=''Drag Race'' Renewed for Season 11 |url=http://tvline.com/2018/06/13/rupauls-drag-race-renewed-season-11-untucked/ |website=[[TVLine]] |accessdate=June 13, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613145952/http://tvline.com/2018/06/13/rupauls-drag-race-renewed-season-11-untucked/ |archivedate=June 13, 2018 |location=United States |date=June 13, 2018}}</ref>

==Specials==

===''RuPaul’s Drag Race: Green Screen Christmas'' (2015)===
On December 13, 2015, Logo aired a seasonal themed episode of ''RuPaul's Drag Race''. The non-competitive special episode was released in conjunction with RuPaul's holiday album ''[[Slay Belles]]'' and featured music videos for songs from the album. The cast included RuPaul, Michelle Visage, [[Siedah Garrett]], and [[Todrick Hall]], and former contestants, including [[Alyssa Edwards]], [[Laganja Estranja]], [[Latrice Royale]], [[Sutan Amrull|Raja]], and [[Shangela]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ru-Cap “RuPaul’s Green Screen Christmas” Extravaganza With A TON of GIFs!|url=https://worldofwonder.net/ru-live-rupauls-green-screen-christmas-with-a-ton-of-gifs/ |website=[[ World of Wonder (company)|WOW]]|accessdate=November 1, 2018|date=December 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= ‘RuPaul’s Drag Race: Green Screen Christmas’ Holiday Special to Air Dec. 13|url= https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/heres-how-you-can-ring-in-the-holidays-with-rupaul_us_565f1394e4b072e9d1c437f2?guccounter=1 |website=[[Huffington Post]] |accessdate= November 1, 2018|date=December 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= This Sneak Peek of RuPaul's Drag Race Christmas Special Will Jingle Your Bells |url= https://www.tvguide.com/news/rupauls-drag-race-christmas-special-happy-holigays/ |website=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=November 1, 2018 |date= December 1, 2015}}</ref>

===''RuPaul’s Drag Race Holi-slay Spectacular'' (2018)===
{{Main|RuPaul's Drag Race Holi-slay Spectacular}}
On November 1, 2018, VH1 announced a seasonal themed special episode of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' scheduled to air on December 7, 2018. The special will see eight former contestants compete for the title of America’s first Drag Race Christmas Queen.<ref>{{cite web |last=Nolfi |first=Joel |title=RuPaul's Drag Race to reunite eight queens for holiday competition episode|url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/11/01/rupaul-drag-race-holiday-special-premiere-date/ |website=[[EW.com]]|accessdate=November 1, 2018|date=November 1, 2018}}</ref> In the same announcement, the eight contestants confirmed to be competing are [[Eureka O'Hara]], [[Jasmine Masters]], [[Kim Chi (drag queen)|Kim Chi]], [[Latrice Royale]], [[Mayhem Miller (drag queen)| Mayhem Miller]], [[Shangela]], Sonique, and [[Trixie Mattel]].<ref>{{cite web |last=McHenry |first=Jackson |title=It’s the Most Ru-nderful Time of the Year! Drag Race Is Making a Holi-Slay Spectacular|url=http://www.vulture.com/2018/11/rupauls-drag-race-holiday-spectacular.html |website=[[Vulture.com|Vulture]]|accessdate=November 1, 2018|date=November 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Colburn |first=Randall |title=RuPaul to crown America's first Drag Race Xmas Queen on new holiday special|url=https://news.avclub.com/rupaul-to-crown-americas-first-drag-race-xmas-queen-on-1830156705 |website=AV Club |accessdate=November 1, 2018|date=November 1, 2018}}</ref>

==Music==
{{main|RuPaul discography}}
Almost all music used in the series comes from RuPaul's albums: ''[[Champion (RuPaul album)|Champion]]'', ''[[Glamazon (album)|Glamazon]]'', ''[[Born Naked]]'', ''[[Realness (RuPaul album)|Realness]]'', ''[[Butch Queen]]'', and ''[[American (RuPaul album)|American]]''.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}} Exceptions are songs used during the lip-sync portion of the show.

===Runway===
Songs used while the contestants walk the runway have been:
* "[[Cover Girl (RuPaul song)|Cover Girl]]" from ''Champion'' (season 1)
* "[[Jealous of My Boogie|Jealous of My Boogie" (Gomi & RasJek Mix)]] from ''Jealous of My Boogie - The RuMixes'' (season 2)
* "Champion" (DJ BunJoe's Olympic Mix) from ''Champion'' (season 3)
* "Glamazon" from ''Glamazon'' (season 4)
* "I Bring the Beat" from ''Glamazon'' (season 5)
* "Sissy That Walk" from ''[[Born Naked]]'' (season 6–7)
* "The Realness" from ''Realness'' (season 8)
* Unreleased remix of "Category Is..." (season 9)
* "Snapshot" from ''Remember Me: Essential, Vol. 1'' (season 10)

===''The Covergurlz'' & ''Covergurlz 2''===
RuPaul confirmed on Twitter that a new album, in which each of the Season 6 contestants covered a song from his catalog, would be released. The album, titled [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 6)#RuPaul Presents: The CoverGurlz|''RuPaul Presents: The CoverGurlz'']], was released on January 28, 2014<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/ru...lz/id798824990|title=iTunes - Music - RuPaul Presents the CoverGurlz by RuPaul|work=iTunes}}</ref>

Similar to Season 6, each of the season 7's contestants covered a song that was previously recorded by RuPaul. The album is titled [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 7)#RuPaul Presents: CoverGurlz2|''RuPaul Presents: CoverGurlz2'']] and was released on February 3, 2015. The album also features the single "New York City Beat", a song by RuPaul featuring Michelle Visage.<ref name="covergurlz itunes">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/rupaul-presents-covergurlz2/id960466886|title=iTunes - Music - RuPaul Presents CoverGurlz2 by RuPaul|work=iTunes}}</ref>

===Other music===
Five promotional singles have been released from the show's respective casts. The first single, titled "[[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 5)#Episode Six: Can I Get An Amen?|Can I Get an Amen]]", was released in 2013, and featured the eight remaining contestants of the [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 5)#Contestants|season 5 cast]]. "Can I Get an Amen" was a parody of the charity single "[[We Are the World]]", and featured [[Alaska Thunderfuck 5000|Alaska]], [[Alyssa Edwards]], Coco Montrese, [[Detox Icunt|Detox]], Ivy Winters, Jade Jolie, [[Jinkx Monsoon]], and Roxxxy Andrews. The second single to surface from the show was a rap song titled "[[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 6)#Episode Six: Oh No She Betta Don't!|Oh No She Better Don't]]," and was released in 2014. The single featured the remaining nine contestants of the [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 6)#Contestants|season 6 cast]]: [[Adore Delano]], BenDeLaCreme, [[Bianca Del Rio]], [[Courtney Act]], Darienne Lake, Joslyn Fox, Laganja Estranja, Milk, and Trinity K. Bonet. The third single, "Read U Wrote U", was released in 2016. It featured the top 4 contestants from All Stars 2; Alaska, [[Katya Zamolodchikova|Katya]], Detox & Roxxxy Andrews. "Read U Wrote U" is the most successful of the ''Drag Race'' promotional singles, peaking at number 29 on the Dance and Electronic Charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/rupaul/chart-history/dance-electronic-songs/song/997346|title=RuPaul Read U Wrote U Chart History|publisher=}}</ref> The fourth single, "Category Is", featured the top 4 contestants from season 9; Peppermint, Sasha Velour, Trinity Taylor, & Shea Couleé. It was released on iTunes on April 20, 2018.<ref>Cite web|url=http://worldofwonder.net/gag-rupauls-drag-race-season-9s-category-is-is-now-available-on-itunes/</ref> The fifth single, "Kitty Girl", featured the top 4 contestants from All Stars Season 3; Kennedy Davenport, Shangela, Bebe Zahara Benet & Trixie Mattel. It charted at number 99 on the UK Singles Chart giving RuPaul his first UK chart entry in 20 years. 
<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/sales-of-rupauls-kitty-girl-surge-1160-after-drag-race-all-stars-3-finale__22340/ |title=Sales of Rupaul's Kitty Girl surge 1160% after Drag Race All Stars 3 finale |date=March 19, 2018 |last=Copsey |first=Rob |work=[[Official Charts Company|Official Charts]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart-update/20180319/7501u/ |title=Official Singles Chart Update Top 100 |date=March 19, 2018 |work=Official Charts}}</ref> The sixth single, "American", featured the top 4 contestants from Season 10; Aquaria, Asia O'Hara, Eureka O'Hara & Kameron Michaels.

Following ''Drag Race'', many contestants from the show have delved into music careers, with some garnering significant success. Albums released by the shows alumni include ''[[PG-13 (album)|PG-13]]'', by season 4 winner [[Sharon Needles]]; ''[[Two Birds (album)|Two Birds]]'' and ''[[One Stone]]'', both by All Stars 3 winner [[Trixie Mattel]]; ''[[Till Death Do Us Party]]'', by season 6 runner-up [[Adore Delano]]; and [[Call My Life]] by season 10 contestant [[Blair St. Clair]]. 

==Related media==
;''RuPaul's Drag U'' (2010–2012)
:''[[RuPaul's Drag U]]'' is a [[Spin-off (media)|spin-off]] that ran from 2010 to 2012. In each episode, three women are paired with former ''Drag Race'' contestants ("Drag Professors"), who give them [[Drag (clothing)|drag]] [[makeover]]s and help them to access their "inner divas".<ref name="FBDragU">{{cite web| last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Facebook Rupaul's Drag U | work = | publisher = | date =April 12, 2010 |url=https://www.facebook.com/RuPaulsDragU?v=info | doi = | accessdate =April 12, 2010 }}</ref> Since each episode was taped in Los Angeles over a period of one month, most of the professors were queens living in Southern California.
;''RuPaul's Drag Race: All Stars'' (2012–)
:''[[RuPaul's Drag Race: All Stars]]'' is a recurring miniseries in which past contestants compete for a spot in the Drag Race Hall of Fame. The show's format is similar to that of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'', with challenges and a panel of judges. The first ''All Stars'' started six months after the conclusion of ''Drag Race'''s [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 4)|fourth season]]. 12 queens from the first four seasons competed over the six episodes. The second ''All Stars'' competition aired in 2016, a few months after the [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 8)|season eight]] finale. This season featured ten queens, selected from the second through to the seventh season, competing in 8 episodes, with a special reunion episode. The third ''All Stars'' season was announced in August 2017, and the cast was revealed during a VH1 television special, which aired on October 20, 2017. Ten queens selected from the first through ninth season competed over the course of 8 episodes.
;''The Switch'' (2015–)
:''[[The Switch Drag Race|The Switch]]'' is a licensed [[glocalization]] of ''Drag Race'' that premiered in October 2015 on Chilean television channel [[Mega (Chilean television channel)|Mega]]. As in ''Drag Race'', queens compete in "mini challenges" and a main challenge, and are evaluated by a panel of judges. Similarly to ''Drag Race'', ''The Switch'' requires contenstants to lip sync, dance, and perform impersonations.
;''[[Drag Race Thailand]]'' (2018–)
:In October 2017, it was announced that [[Kantana Group]] had acquired the rights to produce its own version of ''Drag Race''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://instinctmagazine.com/post/thailand-bought-rights-produce-its-own-rupauls-drag-race |title=Thailand Bought The Rights To Produce Its Own RuPaul's Drag Race |date=October 19, 2017}}</ref> Season 1 of ''Drag Race Thailand'' was met with successful ratings on [[Thailand|Thai]] television. It was later announced that the first season will premiere in the [[United States]] in May 2018. The first season also made stirs in the Asian LGBT community, the most prominent of which was a campaign to establish versions of ''Drag Race'' in the [[Philippines]] and [[Taiwan]] as well, two of the most LGBT-accepting nations in all of [[Asia]].<ref>https://www.rappler.com/entertainment/spotlight/181956-rupaul-drag-race-rodrigo-duterte-donald-trump</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=By bluebay700 |url=http://bluebay700.com/2017/06/10/philippines-was-well-represented-at-rupauls-drag-race-season-9-finale/ |title=Philippines Was Well Represented At RuPaul’s Drag Race Season 9 Finale |publisher=bluebay700 |date=2017-06-10 |accessdate=2018-09-19}}</ref>

;Brazilian localization (2018)
:In August 2017, a Brazilian version of the show was announced. It is scheduled to air in late 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://f5.folha.uol.com.br/colunistas/fernando-oliveira/2017/08/drag-rupaul-vira-ao-pais-para-reality-show.shtml |title=Drag RuPaul virá ao país para reality show |work=[[Folha de S.Paulo]] |date=August 23, 2017}}</ref>
;''[[Dancing Queen (U.S. TV series)|Dancing Queen]]'' (2018)
:In April 2013, RuPaul confirmed that he plans to [[Executive producer|executive-produce]] a spin-off of ''Drag Race'' that stars season-five contestant [[Alyssa Edwards]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Lloyd|first=Sarah Anne|url=http://www.wetpaint.com/network/articles/whoa-rupaul-took-alyssa-edwards-to-the-mtv-movie-awards|title=Whoa Rupaul Took Alyssa Edwards to the MTV Movie Awards|publisher=Wetpaint|accessdate=April 24, 2013}}</ref> Alyssa Edwards has confirmed that the spin-off's title is ''Beyond Belief'' (later retitled as ''Dancing Queen''),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dragofficial.com/1/post/2013/06/update-on-alyssa-edwards-new-spin-off.html|title=Update on Alyssa Edwards' New Spin-Off 'Beyond Belief'|work= Drag Official}}</ref> and that his dance company in [[Mesquite, Texas]] is the setting.<ref>{{cite web|last=Renzi|first=Dan|url=http://www.queerty.com/no-t-no-shade-alyssa-edwards-takes-her-next-step-20130615/|title=No T No Shade Alyssa Edwards Takes Her Next Step|publisher=Queerty|accessdate=July 12, 2013}}</ref> The series aired on Netflix on October 5, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8471649/drag-race-alyssa-edwards-netflix-docu-series-trailer|title='Drag Race's Alyssa Edwards to Star in Netflix Docu-Series: Watch the Trailer|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/rupauls-drag-race-alyssa-edwards-star-dancing-queen-docuseries-netflix-1202450180/|title=‘RuPaul’s Drag Race’ Alum Alyssa Edwards To Star In ‘Dancing Queen’ Docuseries On Netflix|last=Petski|first=Denise|date=2018-08-22|work=Deadline|access-date=2018-08-25|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/08/22/alyssa-edwards-dancing-queen-trailer-netflix/|title='RuPaul's Drag Race' star Alyssa Edwards battles angry dance moms in 'Dancing Queen' series trailer|work=EW.com|access-date=2018-08-25|language=en}}</ref>
;British localization (TBD)
:In April 2014, [[chat show]] host and television presenter [[Jonathan Ross]] told the ''[[Daily Star (British newspaper)|Daily Star]]'' that a UK version of the show was being planned, fronted by [[Jodie Harsh]] instead of RuPaul. Ross said, "I’ve been working with Jodie on a UK version of RuPaul's Drag Race. Unfortunately, we have had to take a break because of some family issues. But we’re hoping to pick it up again in the near future. I am definitely serving ‘middle-aged-realness!’"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/showbiz/goss/372632/Jonathan-Ross-starts-hunt-for-Britain-s-next-drag-starstar|title=Jonathan Ross starts hunt for Britain's next drag starstar - Wired - Latest Celebrity Gossip, Controversy & News - Daily Star|work=Dailystar.co.uk}}</ref> RuPaul has since explained, "I think that because truTV has brought all the seasons of ''Drag Race'' to the UK I think that that might be something that will happen much sooner…. I think that people will fall so in love with the show, I think that the hunger and the thirst for a UK version will probably happen. That's my prediction."<ref name="movie">{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/rupaul-reveals-rupauls-drag-race-6294306|title=RuPaul reveals RuPaul's Drag Race MOVIE in new magazine dedicated to all things drag|author=Carl Greenwood|date=21 August 2015|work=mirror}}</ref> To coincide with TruTV airing new seasons of the show in the UK, RuPaul hosted a competition to find a UK Ambassador for ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' with judges Jonathan Ross and [[Katie Price]] in May 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/rupauls-drag-race-uk-jonathan-5775001|title=RuPaul's Drag Race UK: Jonathan Ross joins search for a drag queen superstar to represent us|author=Carl Greenwood|date=27 May 2015|work=mirror}}</ref> The Vivienne, a drag queen from [[Liverpool]], won the competition and created [[Video blog|vlogs]] to accompany ''Drag Race'' episodes on truTV as well as visiting the set for the eighth season of ''Drag Race'' in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.out.com/popnography/2015/5/29/rupaul-crowns-first-ever-uk-drag-ambassador-vivienne|title=RuPaul Crowns First Ever UK Drag Ambassador: The Vivienne|work=out.com}}</ref>
;Feature film (TBD)
:In August 2015, RuPaul revealed that a movie featuring all of the contestants was in the works. "We've got a director for it, we've got a light script, but it just needs a little more retooling and scheduling."<ref name="movie" />

