==Awards and nominations==
{{Main|List of awards and nominations received by RuPaul's Drag Race}}
''RuPaul's Drag Race'' has been nominated for 23 [[Emmy Award]]s, and won nine. It has also been nominated for nine Reality Television Awards, winning three, and nominated for six [[NewNowNext Awards]], winning three.

==Critical reception==
Early seasons of ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' were criticized for appearing to favor 'glamorous' drag queens over comedic or [[Camp (style)|camp]] queens. For example, Popbytes commented ''Drag Race'' has been accused numerous times of keeping some of the more unpleasant but 'feminine' queens in the competition for the sake of drama {{citation needed|date=September 2017}}. However, Common Sense Media commented, "''RuPaul's Drag Race'' combines the fashion design drama of ''[[Project Runway]]'' with the modeling excitement of ''[[America's Next Top Model]]'' to create an entertainingly voyeuristic glimpse into the performance art world of drag queens. There's plenty of over-the-top stuff, but rather than simply treating drag performers as people to be laughed at and/or scorned, the show also focuses on the hard work and talent that goes into drag performances."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.commonsensemedia.org/tv-reviews/rupauls-drag-race|title=RuPaul's Drag Race|work=commonsensemedia.org}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' cited the elimination of comedian and eventual season two fan favorite [[Pandora Boxx]] as the season's most controversial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/recap/rupauls-drag-race-season-2-episode-8/|title='RuPaul's Drag Race' recap: Drag mamas, Cloris Leachman, and the season's most controversial elimination!|publisher=}}</ref>

===Controversy===
In March 2014, ''Drag Race'' sparked controversy over the use of the term "[[shemale]]" in the season 6 mini challenge [[RuPaul's Drag Race (season 6)#Controversy|"Female or She-male?"]].<ref name="Nichols"/> [[Logo TV|Logo]] has since removed the segment from all platforms and has addressed the allegations of transphobia by removing the "You've got she-mail" intro from new episodes of the series. This was replaced with, "She done already done had herses!"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/04/14/rupauls-drag-race-transphobic-slur_n_5142855.html?ncid=fcbklnkushpmg00000050|title='RuPaul's Drag Race' To Refrain From Using 'Transphobic Slur' In Wake Of Controversy|author=James Nichols|date=April 14, 2014|accessdate=April 14, 2014}}</ref>

Host RuPaul additionally came under fire for comments made in an interview with ''[[The Guardian]]'', in which he stated he would "probably not" allow a transgender contestant to compete on ''Drag Race.''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2018/mar/03/rupaul-drag-race-big-f-you-to-male-dominated-culture|title=RuPaul: ‘Drag is a big f-you to male-dominated culture’|last=Aitkenhead|first=Decca|date=2018-03-03|website=The Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-08-01}}</ref> RuPaul compared transgender drag performers to doping athletes on his Twitter,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rodriguez |first1=Mathew |title=RuPaul Just Tweeted About 'Performance Enhancing Drugs' After Trans Remarks Controversy |url=https://www.intomore.com/culture/rupaul-just-tweeted-about-performance-enhancing-drugs-after-trans-remarks-controversy/46045dd8ceae4b4f |work=INTO |date=5 March 2018 |language=en}}</ref> and has since apologized.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nolfi |first1=Joel |title=RuPaul tweets 'regret' over controversial transgender comments |url=http://ew.com/news/2018/03/05/rupaul-apology-transgender-comments/ |accessdate=1 August 2018 |work=EW.com |date=March 5, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Season nine winner, Sasha Velour, has expressed her disagreement via Twitter, stating "My drag was born in a community full of trans women, trans men, and gender non-conforming folks doing drag. That’s the real world of drag, like it or not. I thinks it’s fabulous and I will fight my entire life to protect and uplift it".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leighton-Dore |first1=Samuel |title=Sasha Velour has more to say on RuPaul's trans comments |url=https://www.sbs.com.au/topics/sexuality/fast-lane/article/2018/03/16/sasha-velour-has-more-say-rupauls-trans-comments |work=SBS |date=16 March 2018 |language=en}}</ref>

==International broadcast==
* '''Australia''': In Australia, lifestyle channel [[LifeStyle YOU]]<ref>[http://www.lifestyleyou.com.au/tv/ru-pauls-drag-race/ ''RuPaul's Drag Race'' at lifestyleyou.com.au] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100403030756/http://www.lifestyleyou.com.au/tv/ru-pauls-drag-race/ |date=2010-04-03 }}</ref> regularly shows and re-screens seasons 1-7, including Untucked. In addition, free-to-air channel SBS2 began screening the first season on August 31, 2013. On March 13, 2017, it was announced that [[Stan (company)|Stan]] will fast track season 9 (including Untucked). Additionally, Stan streams all episodes from seasons 1-10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/topics/sexuality/fast-lane/article/2017/03/13/rupauls-drag-race-season-9-being-fast-tracked-australia|title='RuPaul's Drag Race' season 9 is being fast tracked to Australia|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvtonight.com.au/2013/08/airdate-rupauls-drag-race.html|title=Airdate: RuPaul's Drag Race|work=TV Tonight}}</ref>
* '''Brazil''': In January 2011, [[VH1 Brasil]] aired season 2 followed by season 1, season 3, and season 4.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.facebook.com/story.php?story_fbid=1889208630348&id=145262062198541&_rdr|title=RuPaul, a drag queen mais famosa do mundo, apresenta a competição mais colorida da televisão. Quintas, às 21h,|work=www.facebook.com/vh1brasil}}</ref> The season 7 was aired on the [[Multishow]] cable network every Monday at 11:30pm in August 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://multishow.globo.com/programas/rupauls-drag-race/videos/4286476.htm|title=O reality RuPaul's Drag Race chega em agosto no Multishow|work=multishow.globo.com}}</ref> The season 8 was premiered on April 2017 in [[Comedy Central (Latin America)|Comedy Central]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://snack.comedycentral.com.br/2017/03/rupauls-drag-race-vem-ai/|title=RuPaul's Drag Race vem aí!|work=comedycentral.com.br}}</ref> Only season 8–9 is available on [[Netflix]].
* '''Canada''': The series airs on [[OutTV (Canada)|OutTV]] in Canada at the same time as the US airing. Unlike Logo, OutTV continues to broadcast ''Untucked'' immediately after each ''Drag Race'' episode.<ref name=tbivision>[http://tbivision.com/news/2017/01/new-owners-ceo-canadian-lgbt/698081/ "New owners, CEO for Canadian LGBT net"]. ''TBI Vision'', January 12, 2017.</ref>
* '''Finland''': In 2010, [[Finland|Finnish]] channel TVViisi aired the second season, and during fall 2018 [[Sub (TV channel)|Sub]] will broadcast the show starting from the sixth season, following with the All Stars-seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/subsuomi/photos/a.428770311963.201542.91583001963/10155597146716964/?type=3|title=
Tätä on kysytty ja toivottu! Vihdoin voidaan varmistaa, että syksyllä Subille saapuu: RuPaul’s Drag Race!,|work=www.facebook.com/subsuomi}}</ref>
* '''Germany''': During summer 2009, [[TIMM (TV)|TIMM]]&nbsp;– a former gay television channel from Germany&nbsp;– aired the first season every Friday night.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timm.de/program/series/1474562|title=Burkhard H. Timm - Startseite|work=Burkhard H. Timm}}</ref> [[TLC (Germany)|TLC]] aired seasons two to six, before the rights for the show went to [[Netflix]]. The streaming service has released the show since season seven onwards.
* '''Hungary''': In [[Hungary]], the show aired on [[:hu:FEM3|FEM3]] channel as ''RuPaul&nbsp;– Drag Queen leszek!'' ("''RuPaul&nbsp;– I'll be Drag Queen!''").<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.port.hu/pls/fi/films.film_page?i_film_id=113186|title=RuPaul - Drag Queen leszek!|work=PORT.hu}}</ref>
* '''Ireland''': In Ireland, season 2 to season 8 of the programme were available on Netflix; As of the release of Season 10, only seasons 8 & 9 are available. Netflix has started airing season 10 episodes one day after they air in the USA. 
* '''Latin America''': In January 2011, [[VH1 (Latin America)|VH1 Latin America]] aired season 2 followed by season 1, season 3, and season 4.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1la.com/tv/rupaul-drag-race/|title=VH1 SHOWS - RUPAUL'S DRAG RACE|work=VH1 Latin America}}</ref> The season 8 was premiered on April 2017 in [[Comedy Central (Latin America)|Comedy Central]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvlatina.tv/tvcanales/comedy-central-estrena-octavo-ciclo-de-rupauls-drag-race/|title=Comedy Central - RUPAUL'S DRAG RACE|work=Comedy Central Latin America}}</ref>
* '''Spain''': On 19 September 2016, free-to-air channel [[:es:Ten (canal de televisión)|TEN]] began screening the series from season 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bluper.elespanol.com/noticias/rupaul-reinas-del-drag-estreno-quinta-temporada-ten-19-septiembre|title=LA 5ª TEMPORADA DE 'RUPAUL: REINAS DEL DRAG' LLEGA A TEN ESTE LUNES, 19 DE SEPTIEMBRE|work=El Español}}</ref>
* '''Sweden''': Season 8 of the series currently airs on [[OutTV (Europe)|OutTV]] on Thursdays at 20:00.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.out.tv/se/rupaul's-drag-race-ny-säsong/nieuws/item?801982|title=RuPauls dragrace|work=OUTtv Sverige}}</ref>
* '''The Philippines''': Season 3 was aired on the [[ABS-CBN]]-owned [[Velvet (TV channel)|Velvet]] cable network every Tuesday at 11&nbsp;pm with ''RuPaul's Drag Race: Untucked'', airing directly after the show. Season 4 started airing on April 17, 2012 on the same network.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=310831608968704&set=a.157788814272985.54286.157755517609648&type=1|title=Velvet Channel - Timeline Photos - Facebook|work=facebook.com}}</ref>
* '''UK''': [[E4 (channel)|E4]] aired season 1 in 2009, followed by season 2 in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tellymix.co.uk/reality-tv/214917-start-your-engines-rupauls-drag-race-returns-to-the-uk-on-trutv.html|title=Start your engines! RuPaul's Drag Race returns to the UK on truTV|work=Channel 4}}</ref> Since its success on Netflix in the UK,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/11639133/Which-RuPaul-Drag-Queen-are-you-Find-out-with-our-quiz.html|title=Which RuPaul Drag Queen are you? Find out with our quiz|date=29 May 2015|work=Telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> [[TruTV (UK and Ireland)|TruTV]] acquired the broadcast rights for all eight seasons of the show including ''Untucked'' episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a635037/rupauls-drag-race-coming-to-trutv-uk-in-june.html#~p9Y2NBI5d2xMM9|title=RuPaul's Drag Race coming to truTV UK in June|work=digitalspy.co.uk}}</ref> In June 2015, TruTV started airing two episodes of the show a week, starting with season 4, followed by ''All Stars'', then season 5. As of May 2018, the series airs on VH1 UK Monday-Thursday at 11pm, beginning with All Stars series 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/vh1|title=VH1 UK Schedule|date=1 May 2018|work=mtv.co.uk}}</ref> 
* '''Thailand''': Seasons 2–8 are available to stream on LINE TV.

